   <titles>
      <title>The Absolute Value Operation</title>
      <plain.title>Absolute Value Operation</plain.title>
   </titles>
   <intro>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>In this section we use the ordering structure on the real number system to define the absolute value operation. We then establish its basic properties.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </intro>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <def type="Definition" id="Def_AbsoluteValueR">
               <caption>Absolute value operation on <math>
                     <latex>\RNr</latex>
                  </math>
               </caption>
               <associate type="Explanation">
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>Explanation</info.caption>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Read this as: ‘The absolute value of x is defined to be x if 0 is less than or equal to x, and is defined to be negative x if x is less than or equal to 0.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </associate>
               <associate type="Explanation">
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>Explanation</info.caption>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>This definition makes sense because we know from the totality property of the ordering on <math>
                              <latex>\RNr</latex>
                           </math> that one of the two statements ‘<math>
                              <latex>0\leq x</latex>
                           </math>’ and ‘<math>
                              <latex>x\leq 0</latex>
                           </math>’ always applies. Moreover, we proved that, if <math>
                              <latex>x\leq 0</latex>
                           </math>, then <math>
                              <latex>0\leq -x</latex>
                           </math>. So <math>
                              <latex>0\leq \Abs{x}</latex>
                           </math> always.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </associate>
               <associate type="Comment">
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>Comment</info.caption>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Notice that we do not require a new assumption in the form of an axiom to introduce the absolute value of a real number. Rather this is a construction which can be performed based on axioms and properties discussed earlier.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </associate>
               <def.body>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>The absolute value, or norm, of <math>
                           <latex>x\in \RNr</latex>
                        </math> is
				</para.body>
                     <index.glossary>
                        <term>absolute valued</term>
                        <term>of a number in <math>
                              <latex>\RNr</latex>
                           </math>
                        </term>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>The absolute value, or norm, of <math>
                                    <latex>x\in \RNr</latex>
                                 </math> is
							</para.body>
                              <index.symbol>
                                 <symbol>
                                    <math>
                                       <latex>\Abs{x}</latex>
                                    </math>
                                 </symbol>
                                 <info>
                                    <para>
                                       <para.body>The absolute value of <math>
                                             <latex>x\in \RNr</latex>
                                          </math>
                                       </para.body>
                                    </para>
                                 </info>
                              </index.symbol>
                              <index.glossary>
                                 <term>absolute value of <math>
                                       <latex>x\in \RNr</latex>
                                    </math>
                                 </term>
                              </index.glossary>
                              <index.glossary>
                                 <term>norm of <math>
                                       <latex>x\in \RNr</latex>
                                    </math>
                                 </term>
                              </index.glossary>
                           </para>
                           <math.display>
                              <latex>
								
\Abs{x}\ :=\ \left\{
\aligned
x &amp;\quad \text{if $0\leq x$} \\
-x &amp;\quad \text{if $x\leq 0$}
\endaligned
\right.

							</latex>
                           </math.display>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                  </para>
                  <math.display>
                     <latex>
					
\Abs{x}\ :=\ \left\{
\aligned
x &amp;\quad \text{if $0\leq x$} \\
-x &amp;\quad \text{if $x\leq 0$}
\endaligned
\right.

				</latex>
                  </math.display>
               </def.body>
            </def>
            <para>
               <para.body>Let us now establish the most basic properties of the absolute value operation.</para.body>
            </para>
